
=Definition=

From the Wikipedia:

"An oikos (ancient Greek: οἶκος, plural: οἶκοι; English prefix: eco- for ecology and economics) is the ancient Greek equivalent of a household, house, or family.

An oikos was the basic unit of society in most Greek city-states, and included the head of the oikos (usually the oldest male), his immediate family (wife and children), and slaves living together in one domestic setting.[1] Large oikoi also had farms that were usually tended by the slaves, which were also the basic agricultural unit of the ancient economy."
(http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oikos)


